05157nam a22007815i 9781477308295DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20212016txu    fo  d z      eng d  a2015035742  a97814773082957 a10.7560/3081652doi  a(DE-B1597)586540  a(OCoLC)1269269062  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX00aJV6347b.E73 2016 7aSOC0000002bisacsh04a365/.43089680732231 aEscobar, Martha D., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aCaptivity Beyond Prisons :bCriminalization Experiences of Latina (Im)migrants /cMartha D. Escobar. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©2016  a1 online resource (261 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tAbbreviations -- tIntroduction: Shifting the Conversation from (Im)migrant Rights to Abolition -- t1. Understanding the Roots of Latina (Im)migrants’ Captivity -- t2. Reinforcing Gendered Racial Boundaries: Unintended Consequences of (Im)migrant Rights Discourse -- t3. Violent Formations: Criminalizing and Disciplining (Im)migrant Women -- t4. Domesticating (Im)migration: Coordinating State Violence beyond the Nation-State -- t5. Emancipation Is Not Freedom: A Reflection and Critique of Advocacy Abolition -- tConclusion: Envisioning and Performing Freedom -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aToday the United States leads the world in incarceration rates. The country increasingly relies on the prison system as a “fix” for the regulation of societal issues. Captivity Beyond Prisons is the first full-length book to explicitly link prisons and incarceration to the criminalization of Latina (im)migrants. Starting in the 1990s, the United States saw tremendous expansion in the number of imprisoned (im)migrants, specifically Latinas/os. Consequently, there was also an increase in the number of deportations. In addition to regulating society, prisons also serve as a reproductive control strategy, both in preventing female inmates from having children and by separating them from their families. With an eye to racialized and gendered technologies of power, Escobar argues that incarcerated Latinas are especially depicted as socially irrecuperable because they are not considered useful within the neoliberal labor market. This perception impacts how they are criminalized, which is not limited to incarceration but also extends to and affects Latina (im)migrants’ everyday lives. Escobar also explores the relationship between the immigrant rights movement and the prison abolition movement, scrutinizing a variety of social institutions working on solutions to social problems that lead to imprisonment. Accessible to both academics and those in the justice and social service sectors, Escobar’s book pushes readers to consider how, even in radical spaces, unequal power relations can be reproduced by the very entities that attempt to undo them.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aEmigration and immigration lawxUnited States. 0aEmigration and immigration lawzUnited States. 0aEmigration and immigrationxSocial aspects. 0aEmigration and immigrationxWomenxUnited States. 0aEmigration and immigrationxWomenzUnited States. 0aHispanic American womenxSocial conditions. 0aHispanic American womenzUnited StatesxSocial conditions. 0aImmigrantsxGovernment policyxUnited States. 0aImmigrantsxGovernment policyzUnited States. 0aWomen illegal aliensxSocial conditionsxUnited States. 0aWomen illegal alienszUnited StatesxSocial conditions. 0aWomen immigrantsxSocial conditionsxUnited States. 0aWomen immigrantszUnited StatesxSocial conditions. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisa